<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>7819</anchor> <rss>jms-0009.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-0009</addr>  <route>jms-0009.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>1</month> <day>18</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Kernel</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathcal {A}</tex> be a <link href="jms-000B.xml" type="local" title="Category with zero morphisms">category with zero morphisms</link>. Then the <em>kernel</em> of a morphism <tex>A \xrightarrow {f} B</tex> in <tex>\mathcal {A}</tex> is defined to be a morphism <tex>K \xrightarrow {k}{A}</tex> such that for any <tex>X \xrightarrow {h}A</tex> with <tex>h;f=0</tex>, there exists a unique map <tex>X \xrightarrow {}K</tex>
factoring <tex>X \xrightarrow {h}A</tex> through <tex>K \xrightarrow {k}{A}</tex> in the sense of the diagram below:</p>
  
    <center><img src="resources/e8d070f6c75428a310bd00128541d62f-web.svg"/></center>
  
</mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context/> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>7820</anchor> <rss>jms-000B.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-000B</addr>  <route>jms-000B.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>1</month> <day>18</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Category with zero morphisms</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>A <em>category with zero morphisms</em> is defined to be a category <link href="jms-000H.xml" type="local" title="Enriched category">enriched</link> in the category of pointed sets and strict maps. The distinguished point of <tex>\mathbf {hom} _{ \mathcal {A} } { \mathopen {} \left ( A , B \right ) \mathclose {}}</tex> shall be written <tex>0</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></related> <backlinks><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>7821</anchor> <rss>jms-000A.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Notation</taxon> <addr>jms-000A</addr>  <route>jms-000A.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>1</month> <day>18</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Kernel</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>We will often write <tex>\operatorname {ker} {f} \xrightarrow { i _{ \operatorname {ker} { f } } }A</tex> for the <link href="jms-0009.xml" type="local" title="Kernel">kernel</link> of a map <tex>A \xrightarrow {f}B</tex> in a <link href="jms-000B.xml" type="local" title="Category with zero morphisms">category with zero morphisms</link> <tex>\mathcal {A}</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>7822</anchor> <rss>jms-000C.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Remark</taxon> <addr>jms-000C</addr>  <route>jms-000C.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>1</month> <day>18</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Kernels as equalizers</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Evidently, the <link href="jms-0009.xml" type="local" title="Kernel">kernel</link> of a morphism <tex>A \xrightarrow {f} B</tex> in a <link href="jms-000B.xml" type="local" title="Category with zero morphisms">category with zero morphisms</link> is the <em>equalizer</em> of  <tex>A \xrightarrow {f} B</tex> with the zero morphism <tex>A \xrightarrow {0} B</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" root="false"><frontmatter> <anchor>7823</anchor> <rss>jms-0002.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Definition</taxon> <addr>jms-0002</addr>  <route>jms-0002.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>1</month> <day>17</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Exact terms and complex terms</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\cdots \xrightarrow {}{ A } \xrightarrow { f }{ B } \xrightarrow { g }{ C } \xrightarrow {} \cdots</tex> be a sequence in an abelian category <tex>\mathcal {A}</tex>. The term <tex>B</tex> is called <em>complex</em> when <tex>f;g=0</tex>, and <em>exact</em> when the <link href="jms-0009.xml" type="local" title="Kernel">kernel</link> of <tex>g</tex> is isomorphic to the image of <tex>f</tex>, in other words <tex>\operatorname {ker} {g}= \operatorname {im} {f}</tex>.</p></mainmatter> </tree></backlinks> <references/></backmatter></tree>